# Training a predictive portfolio allocation model end-to-end

A modified Temporal Fusion Transformer with Dirichlet-smoothed labels, cross-entropy loss, and walk-forward purged validation represents the strongest design for this system. The key insight from recent literature is that **training a supervised model on pre-computed optimal weights (the "Decision by Supervised Learning" paradigm) outperforms both two-stage predict-then-optimize and end-to-end Sharpe maximization** in stability and out-of-sample performance. This report provides a complete blueprint—from label construction through architecture selection, loss design, feature engineering, data schema, and practical sourcing—with concrete recommendations at every stage.

The system takes four data modalities (OHLCV, macro, fundamental, sentiment) and outputs a probability simplex over N assets at three horizons simultaneously. Each design choice below is grounded in published research and battle-tested quantitative finance practices.

---

## 1. Constructing Dirichlet-sampled labels without look-ahead bias

### From Dirichlet samples to regression targets

The Dirichlet distribution Dir(α₁, …, αN) is the natural probability distribution over the simplex—vectors of non-negative values summing to 1—making it the canonical tool for sampling candidate portfolio weights. The standard workflow draws K weight vectors from Dir(α), evaluates the Sharpe ratio of each over a forward return window, and selects the best. With α₁ = α₂ = … = αN = 1 (uniform Dirichlet), samples cover the simplex uniformly. Setting all αᵢ > 1 concentrates mass toward equal-weight; all αᵢ < 1 pushes toward concentrated portfolios.

The critical refinement is to **avoid using a single argmax sample as the label**. Instead, select the top-K samples by Sharpe (e.g., K = 50–100), then compute their barycentric mean on the simplex. This ensemble-of-optima approach dramatically reduces label noise—the DSL framework (Kim et al., 2025) demonstrated that deep ensembles of 100 independent runs with averaged weights substantially outperform single-point optima. An even more principled variant fits a Dirichlet distribution to the top-K samples, producing a full distributional label Dir(α̂) rather than a point estimate. A Bayesian shrinkage step further stabilizes labels: **w_smooth = (1 − γ) · w*_optimal + γ · (1/N)**, where γ ∈ [0.1, 0.3] controls shrinkage toward equal-weight. Bodnar et al. (2021, Journal of Banking & Finance) showed this shrinkage consistently improves out-of-sample Sharpe.

### Multi-horizon label design

For simultaneous next-day, next-week, and next-month targets, **run separate Dirichlet optimizations per horizon**. At each date t, compute the Sharpe-optimal weight vector independently over [t+2, t+3] (1-day), [t+2, t+7] (5-day), and [t+2, t+23] (21-day) forward return windows. The 1-day gap between the last feature date and the first label date prevents microstructure leakage. Each horizon produces an independent target vector w^(h) ∈ ℝᴺ on the simplex. Multi-task learning during training handles any tension between horizons—this separation keeps label construction clean while the model learns shared representations across horizons.

### Preventing look-ahead bias in labels

Labels are inherently forward-looking (they encode what the best allocation *would have been*), but features must be strictly causal. The firewall is simple: features at date t use only data from [t − lookback, t − 1]; labels use returns from [t + gap, t + gap + horizon]. Normalization statistics (means, standard deviations) must be computed on expanding or rolling windows ending at t − 1—never on the full dataset. For fundamental data, use the SEC filing date (not the fiscal period end date) to determine when information became public. The Compustat Point-in-Time database or Sharadar fundamentals provide as-reported data with filing timestamps, which is essential since Lyle et al. (2024, Yale) showed that Compustat re-standardization can change quarterly earnings by **100% on average** relative to point-in-time figures.

Incorporate **transaction costs directly into the label-generating optimization** to produce realistic targets:

```
max  w'μ − λw'Σw − γΣ|wᵢ − wᵢ,prev|
s.t. Σwᵢ = 1, wᵢ ≥ 0
```

The turnover penalty γ (calibrated to 10–50 basis points per side) acts as an implicit regularizer. Olivares-Nadal and DeMiguel showed that a quadratic cost model reduces minimum-variance portfolio turnover from **80.84% to 6.44% monthly** while improving out-of-sample performance.

