## 2. Feature engineering across four data modalities

### OHLCV: price, volume, and cross-asset structure

The price/volume feature set should capture momentum, volatility, liquidity, and cross-asset correlation at multiple timescales. Compute **log returns at 1, 5, 21, 63, 126, and 252-day** horizons per ticker. For volatility, the Garman-Klass estimator (incorporating open/high/low/close) provides the best efficiency-simplicity tradeoff, computed at 5, 10, 21, 63, and 252-day rolling windows. Supplement with Yang-Zhang (2000) for robustness to overnight gaps, and include **vol-of-vol** (rolling standard deviation of rolling volatility) as a regime-change indicator.

For cross-asset correlation structure, avoid flattening the full N(N−1)/2 pairwise correlations (intractable for large N). Instead, extract eigenvalue-based summary statistics from the 63-day rolling correlation matrix: the **first eigenvalue's share of total variance** (market factor dominance—high values signal risk-off regimes), the ratio λ₁/λ₂, and the effective number of independent bets (Σλᵢ)²/Σλᵢ². These 3–5 features capture the essential dimensionality of correlation dynamics.

Momentum indicators include RSI at 5, 14, 21, and 63-day windows; MACD (12, 26, 9); and SMA ratios (50/200-day) as trend indicators. For liquidity, use the **Amihud (2002) illiquidity ratio** (|return|/dollar volume, averaged over 21 days)—one of the most cited illiquidity proxies with 12,000+ citations—and volume ratios relative to 20-day moving averages.

Cross-sectionally, compute **percentile ranks** of each feature across all tickers at each date. This relative-strength normalization is standard in factor investing and ensures the model learns which assets are cheap, volatile, or liquid *relative to peers*.

### Macro indicators: solving the mixed-frequency problem

Key macro features include VIX (daily), yield curve spreads—2s10s and 3m10y (daily), Fed funds rate (daily), CPI (monthly), PMI/ISM (monthly), unemployment (monthly), GDP growth (quarterly), and initial jobless claims (weekly). The alignment challenge is that daily models need daily feature vectors.

The practical solution is **forward-fill (last observation carried forward)** for all lower-frequency series, augmented with two critical metadata features per macro variable: `days_since_last_update` and `days_until_next_release` (from economic calendars). Forward-filling is the only valid approach—interpolation uses future information. The MIDAS (Mixed Data Sampling) literature (Ghysels, Santa-Clara & Valkanov, 2005) provides the theoretical foundation, and recent work on Mixed-Frequency Machine Learning (Borup & Schütte, 2022) shows that U-MIDAS with regularization works well within ML frameworks.

**Include all three representations of each macro variable**: levels (capture regime), first differences (capture trend), and surprises (actual minus consensus, standardized). Surprises are the most predictive for short-horizon returns. Heston and Sinha (2016, Federal Reserve) found that negative macro surprises have **delayed effects lasting up to one quarter**, while positive surprises incorporate quickly—motivating the inclusion of decayed surprise features at multiple half-lives.

### Fundamental and earnings data: point-in-time correctness is non-negotiable

Key fundamentals include valuation ratios (P/E, P/B, EV/EBITDA, FCF yield), quality metrics (ROE, ROA, accruals), growth rates (revenue and earnings YoY), and analyst revision momentum. The cardinal rule: **use filing dates, not period-end dates**. Earnings for a fiscal quarter ending December 31 may not be filed until February or March. Wang et al. (2014) showed that using period-end dates instead of actual availability dates inflates earnings-yield factor performance by **60%**.

For earnings surprises, construct Standardized Unexpected Earnings (SUE) as (actual EPS − median analyst consensus) / stock price, using IBES estimates confirmed within 90 days of announcement and split-adjusted. Analyst revision momentum—the change in consensus EPS estimates over 1–3 months—is a strong, well-documented alpha signal.

Normalize fundamentals **cross-sectionally within sectors** at each date. A P/E of 25 means something very different for a tech company versus a utility. Within-sector z-scores remove this heterogeneity. For quality and growth metrics, universe-wide percentile ranks work well.

Survivorship bias is equally critical. Excluding delisted stocks inflates backtested returns by **1.6–2% annually** and can inflate Sharpe ratios by up to 0.5. Use survivorship-bias-free databases (CRSP, Sharadar) and include delisted stocks in training data up to their delisting date with terminal returns.

### Sentiment and NLP signals: FinBERT with exponential decay aggregation

**FinBERT** (Araci, 2019; `ProsusAI/finbert` on HuggingFace) is the recommended sentiment model—a BERT-base architecture fine-tuned on Financial PhraseBank achieving ~89% accuracy on financial news, a **14 percentage point improvement** over generic BERT. It outputs softmax probabilities for positive/negative/neutral classes. VADER is 339× faster but achieves only 44–56% accuracy on financial text. GPT-4 offers marginal improvement at 100×+ cost.

For daily aggregation of multiple headlines per ticker, construct this feature vector:

- Mean sentiment score (P(positive) − P(negative))
- Count of positive, negative, and neutral headlines
- Max positive and max negative sentiment scores
- Total news volume (headline count)
- Sentiment dispersion (standard deviation of scores)

Apply **exponential decay weighting** to historical sentiment with multiple half-lives (1, 3, 5, and 10 days) as separate features: AggSentiment_t = Σ exp(−λk) · Sentiment_{t−k}. This captures both rapid-incorporation positive news effects and the slow-decaying predictive power of negative news documented by Heston and Sinha.

### Normalization strategy summary

| Feature type | Normalization approach |
|---|---|
| Log returns | Already stationary; winsorize at 0.1%/99.9% percentiles |
| Volatility | Per-ticker expanding-window z-score |
| Valuation ratios (P/E, P/B) | Within-sector cross-sectional z-score at each date |
| Macro indicators | Expanding-window z-score (shared across tickers) |
| Sentiment scores | Bounded [−1, 1]; no normalization or cross-sectional rank |
| Volume features | Per-ticker robust scaling (median/IQR) |
| Growth rates, quality metrics | Universe-wide percentile rank |

Apply time-series normalization first (to remove temporal non-stationarity), then cross-sectional normalization (to remove cross-sectional heterogeneity). For fat-tailed features, use **robust scaling** (center on median, scale by IQR) rather than z-score, and log-transform right-skewed features (volume, market cap) before any scaling.

