## 3. Architecture comparison and recommendation

### Why the Temporal Fusion Transformer is the strongest match

The TFT (Lim, Arık, Loeff & Pfister, 2021, International Journal of Forecasting) is purpose-built for exactly this problem's requirements. It natively handles **multi-horizon prediction** (producing outputs at each future step in a single forward pass), **mixed-frequency inputs** via its three-input taxonomy (static covariates for sector/metadata, known future inputs for calendar features and scheduled macro releases, past observed inputs for OHLCV and sentiment), and provides **interpretable variable selection** through learned softmax-weighted Variable Selection Networks. The Gated Residual Networks adaptively apply non-linear processing only where warranted—valuable for noisy financial data.

To adapt TFT for portfolio allocation, replace the quantile regression output heads with **per-horizon softmax heads** that produce weight vectors on the simplex. Add a cross-asset attention layer in the decoder (TFT natively processes per-entity; portfolio allocation requires cross-entity reasoning). For uncertainty quantification, use a **Dirichlet output layer** instead of softmax: the network outputs concentration parameters α via softplus activation, with the mean allocation as αᵢ/Σαⱼ and total concentration S = Σαᵢ encoding prediction confidence. Low-confidence predictions (low S) can trigger a fallback to equal-weight or minimum-variance allocation.

Available implementations include `pytorch-forecasting` (full TFT with Optuna hyperparameter optimization), `Darts`, and Google's reference TensorFlow implementation.

### How alternatives compare

**LSTM/GRU with multi-task heads** is the strongest baseline: a 2–3 layer bidirectional LSTM encoder (128–256 hidden units) with Bahdanau attention feeding three horizon-specific softmax heads. Fischer & Krauss (2018) showed LSTMs are remarkably consistent for financial prediction across training runs, and they remain competitive with smaller datasets. Training is simpler and better understood than Transformer-based approaches.

**PatchTST** (Nie et al., 2023, ICLR) achieves 21% MSE reduction over prior Transformer models on standard benchmarks, but its **channel-independence assumption is disqualifying** for portfolio allocation—it ignores cross-asset correlations that drive diversification benefits. It also lacks support for static covariates, categorical inputs, and has no native multi-horizon granularity support.

**Gradient boosting (XGBoost/LightGBM)** excels with tabular macro and fundamental features—Grinsztajn et al. (2022) showed GBMs are SOTA for heterogeneous tabular data. However, GBMs require flattening temporal structure into hand-crafted lag features, cannot enforce the simplex constraint during training, and need separate models per asset and horizon. Best used as a **component** rather than the full system.

**Hybrid TFT + LightGBM** is the runner-up recommendation: train LightGBM on tabular macro/fundamental features, extract leaf indices as embeddings, and feed these as static covariates into TFT alongside time-series features. This combines GBM's strength with heterogeneous tabular data and TFT's sequential modeling capability.

### Portfolio-specific architectures worth considering

**DeepDow** (Krepl, 2020) is a PyTorch framework purpose-built for end-to-end portfolio optimization, with built-in allocation layers (softmax, sparsemax, differentiable Markowitz via cvxpylayers) and portfolio performance losses (Sharpe, maximum drawdown). It is ideal for rapid prototyping.

**Differentiable convex optimization layers** (Agrawal et al., NeurIPS 2019; cvxpylayers) embed a mean-variance optimizer as a differentiable neural network layer. The network predicts return estimates μ̂ and covariance Σ̂, which feed into a Markowitz layer that outputs guaranteed-feasible weights satisfying all portfolio constraints (max weight, turnover limits, cardinality) by construction. The cost is computational overhead from solving an optimization problem in every forward pass.

### Architecture decision matrix

| Architecture | Multi-horizon | Mixed-frequency | Simplex output | Training complexity | Interpretability | **Overall fit** |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **TFT (modified)** | Native | Native 3-input taxonomy | Softmax/Dirichlet head | Moderate | Variable selection + attention | **Best** |
| Hybrid TFT + GBM | Native | Excellent | Softmax head | High | Tower-specific | **Runner-up** |
| LSTM multi-task | Via multi-head | Manual handling | Natural softmax | Low | Attention + SHAP | **Best baseline** |
| PatchTST | Needs adaptation | No static/categorical | Needs cross-channel mod | Low | Limited | **Not recommended** |
| XGBoost/LightGBM | Separate models | Native tabular | Post-processing only | Very low | SHAP, gain importance | **Tabular component only** |
| DeepDow (e2e) | Single horizon native | Channel-based | Guaranteed by construction | Moderate | Risk contributions | **Best for prototyping** |

