## Conclusion: a concrete implementation roadmap

The strongest design pairs the DSL paradigm (Dirichlet-sampled optimal weights as smoothed cross-entropy targets) with a modified TFT architecture featuring per-horizon softmax or Dirichlet output heads and uncertainty-weighted multi-task learning. Three concrete steps to implementation:

**First**, build the label pipeline: Dirichlet-sample K = 10,000 weight vectors per date, evaluate transaction-cost-penalized Sharpe over each forward horizon, average the top 50–100, apply 10–20% shrinkage toward equal-weight. Store labels with their generating parameters for reproducibility.

**Second**, build features incrementally: start with OHLCV returns and volatility (the strongest signals), add macro features with forward-fill and staleness indicators, integrate point-in-time fundamentals from Sharadar, and finally add FinBERT sentiment with exponential decay aggregation. Each modality should demonstrably improve validation Sharpe before being retained.

**Third**, train with walk-forward purged validation: 3-year rolling training window, 6-month validation, 6-month test, monthly retraining. Use cross-entropy as the primary loss with an auxiliary Sharpe component (α = 0.8 CE + 0.2 Sharpe), uncertainty weighting across horizons, and regime probability features from a pre-trained HMM. Start with the LSTM baseline for fast iteration, then graduate to the modified TFT for production.

The single most impactful design choice is **label quality**—noisy, unsmoothed, single-sample Dirichlet optima will poison any architecture. Invest heavily in the label smoothing and transaction-cost-aware optimization described in Section 1 before tuning model architecture or hyperparameters.